    <node id="Diameter">
      <data key="d0">Diameter</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">Diameter is a measurement used to describe the size of a circular object.&lt;SEP&gt;Diameter measures the size of various components of the pipe flange as specified in ASME B16.5-2013.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-c5f5e2c6bb85dac52bdfa7453796ec77&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-5e85bee1a6414b667d34d9e3ddb49f16</data>
      <data key="d4">ASME B16.5-2013.pdf</data>
      <data key="d5">1776329036</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Neck">
      <data key="d0">Neck</data>
      <data key="d1">artifact</data>
      <data key="d2">Neck refers to a narrow part of a pipe or flange.&lt;SEP&gt;Neck is a component of the pipe flange that connects the hub to the flange as detailed in ASME B16.5-2013.&lt;SEP&gt;Neck is a narrow part connecting two larger parts, often found in flanges.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-c5f5e2c6bb85dac52bdfa7453796ec77&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-5e85bee1a6414b667d34d9e3ddb49f16&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-1359b097a2ba15f87aae6ad689a2a7a9</data>
      <data key="d4">ASME B16.5-2013.pdf</data>
      <data key="d5">1776329036</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Socket Welding">
      <data key="d0">Socket Welding</data>
      <data key="d1">method</data>
      <data key="d2">Socket Welding is a method for connections.&lt;SEP&gt;Socket Welding is a method of connection described in the document.&lt;SEP&gt;Socket Welding is a method of joining pipes where the fitting is inserted into a socket and then welded.&lt;SEP&gt;Socket Welding is a method of joining pipes and fittings where the fitting is inserted into a socket and welded in place as described in ASME B16.5-2013.&lt;SEP&gt;Socket Welding is a method of joining pipes and fittings by welding to a socket.&lt;SEP&gt;Socket welding is a type of welding process used to join pipes and fittings, particularly in smaller sizes.&lt;SEP&gt;Socket Welding is a method of joining pipe flanges as detailed in ASME B16.5-2013.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-c5f5e2c6bb85dac52bdfa7453796ec77&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-8e7b456ed825c2e777586a3d95199f23&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-fb21c0f45d8ce07fe25144ccf2ea7f46&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-4303e33e6d61d4207aeb4ef2e5ef35ea&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-5e85bee1a6414b667d34d9e3ddb49f16&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-90c280892e81306b9d7b1a397e54f308&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-9480b43d18d635d04248ae532bf3633c</data>
      <data key="d4">ASME B16.5-2013.pdf</data>
      <data key="d5">1776329036</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Threaded">
      <data key="d0">Threaded</data>
      <data key="d1">method</data>
      <data key="d2">Threaded components are those with screw threads for joining or securing parts.&lt;SEP&gt;Threaded is a method of connecting pipe flanges and fittings.&lt;SEP&gt;Threaded is a method of connecting pipes and fittings by screwing them together.&lt;SEP&gt;Threaded is a term describing a surface with interlocking teeth for fastening or joining.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-c5f5e2c6bb85dac52bdfa7453796ec77&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-1359b097a2ba15f87aae6ad689a2a7a9&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e253e99ebed9a87e642e60132b8f53d9&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-4151555a834c7ca05d4e5d3bd1722dbb</data>
      <data key="d4">ASME B16.5-2013.pdf</data>
      <data key="d5">1776329036</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Welding">
      <data key="d0">Welding</data>
      <data key="d1">method</data>
      <data key="d2">Welding is a process used to join materials by heating them to a molten state and allowing them to cool together.&lt;SEP&gt;Welding is the process of joining materials, typically metals, by heating them to a point where they melt and fuse together.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-c5f5e2c6bb85dac52bdfa7453796ec77&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-4303e33e6d61d4207aeb4ef2e5ef35ea</data>
      <data key="d4">ASME B16.5-2013.pdf</data>
      <data key="d5">1776329036</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Lapped">
      <data key="d0">Lapped</data>
      <data key="d1">method</data>
      <data key="d2">Lapped joint dimensions are listed in the table.&lt;SEP&gt;Lapped is a method of joining flanges where the edges are overlapped and secured.&lt;SEP&gt;Lapped is a method of joining pipes where the edges of the pipes are overlapped and then welded.&lt;SEP&gt;Lapped components are those with a lapped joint, where the edges are overlapped and secured.&lt;SEP&gt;Lapped is a method of connecting pipe flanges and fittings.&lt;SEP&gt;Lapped is a method of joining pipes and fittings by overlapping them and securing them with a clamp.&lt;SEP&gt;Lapped is a term describing a surface that has been smoothed or polished.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-c5f5e2c6bb85dac52bdfa7453796ec77&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-97992c13bd15395adccdb59249057965&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-1359b097a2ba15f87aae6ad689a2a7a9&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-9dc638f0d9855d44e84fb84b1e17f97e&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-90c280892e81306b9d7b1a397e54f308&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e253e99ebed9a87e642e60132b8f53d9&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-4151555a834c7ca05d4e5d3bd1722dbb</data>
      <data key="d4">ASME B16.5-2013.pdf</data>
      <data key="d5">1776329036</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Class 300 Flanges">
      <data key="d0">Class 300 Flanges</data>
      <data key="d1">artifact</data>
      <data key="d2">Class 300 Flanges are a specific class of flanges with a higher pressure rating than Class 150.&lt;SEP&gt;Class 300 flanges are a type of industrial flange specified in the ASME B16.5-2013 standard.&lt;SEP&gt;Class 300 Flanges are described in detail in Table 11 of ASME B16.5-2013.&lt;SEP&gt;Class 300 Flanges are pipe flanges designed to handle pressures up to 300 pounds per square inch.&lt;SEP&gt;Class 300 Flanges are a specific type of flange with a certain pressure rating.&lt;SEP&gt;Class 300 Flanges are a type of flange mentioned in the document.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-c5f5e2c6bb85dac52bdfa7453796ec77&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-439097792cec97ce9b1b0fb080fa39fc&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e0e55f15f4fdc887c0046610b4244415&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-4a2aa51a49817516d8e488a9d7c544a9&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-43a75c51519a7791b8c4227900b22d57&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c5ace9ce39146c54679f4e19c3434a59&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-51676999d6498cdd7ba881a128f7d63f</data>
      <data key="d4">ASME B16.5-2013.pdf</data>
      <data key="d5">1776329036</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Slip-On">
      <data key="d0">Slip-On</data>
      <data key="d1">method</data>
      <data key="d2">Slip-On is a method of joining pipes and fittings by sliding them onto a flange and securing them with bolts.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-c5f5e2c6bb85dac52bdfa7453796ec77</data>
      <data key="d4">ASME B16.5-2013.pdf</data>
      <data key="d5">1776329036</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Counter-">
      <data key="d0">Counter-</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">Counter- is a prefix used in technical terms to indicate a direction or position relative to another part.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-c5f5e2c6bb85dac52bdfa7453796ec77</data>
      <data key="d4">ASME B16.5-2013.pdf</data>
      <data key="d5">1776329036</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Minimum Welding">
      <data key="d0">Minimum Welding</data>
      <data key="d1">method</data>
      <data key="d2">Minimum welding dimensions are listed in the table.&lt;SEP&gt;Minimum Welding is a method of ensuring a minimum amount of welding is done for safety and quality.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-c5f5e2c6bb85dac52bdfa7453796ec77&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-97992c13bd15395adccdb59249057965</data>
      <data key="d4">ASME B16.5-2013.pdf</data>
      <data key="d5">1776329036</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="ASME 816.5-2013">
      <data key="d0">ASME 816.5-2013</data>
      <data key="d1">artifact</data>
      <data key="d2">ASME 816.5-2013 is a standard document published by ASME International for the design and specification of flanged fittings.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-e6dd99d0d594bbdd5db11e31461478c9</data>
      <data key="d4">ASME B16.5-2013.pdf</data>
      <data key="d5">1776329036</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="2500">
      <data key="d0">2500</data>
      <data key="d1">data</data>
      <data key="d2">2500°C is a temperature point listed in the pressure-temperature ratings table, applicable for certain material groups and pressure classes. This temperature is also a nominal designation for a pressure temperature rating and a working pressure class in the ASME B16.5-2013 standard document. Additionally, 2500 is a specific temperature in degrees Celsius and a dimension value, particularly relevant for ring-joint facings.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-44664e1f68bc892f4b7b0a535c4414b7&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-335c2335ba413830aae1a70244aa5a26&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-fb7c5babdbcd75bdf9752cd67bcadc21&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-94e58312a7e84066f13cc4e7ad9465d9&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-83ab283e30659c933554a033613d2618&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f9faa893029db6f5b871493c6380ddac&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-ddd7861d62bce6b204b2b88ac4982996&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-65a7f7e9599ea4d5c1cfc7d449c5a081&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-7934c8d2ddad5e1d33650120011594a2&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-2879e8ce1f305f975a2bf33f2d701842&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-603423286a04ee8b6cbcba90c6a2736a&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-4bf1cc2e275f250252f3766b12889d76</data>
      <data key="d4">ASME B16.5-2013.pdf</data>
      <data key="d5">1776329036</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="flange">
      <data key="d0">flange</data>
      <data key="d1">artifact</data>
      <data key="d2">Flange is an artifact used in assembling flanged joints.&lt;SEP&gt;Flange is a component used in pipe connections, often referenced in ASME standards.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-e6dd99d0d594bbdd5db11e31461478c9&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-d9d6f8ad3531ac0840bf5ba01dc89ab8</data>
      <data key="d4">ASME B16.5-2013.pdf</data>
      <data key="d5">1776329037</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="875°F">
      <data key="d0">875°F</data>
      <data key="d1">temperature</data>
      <data key="d2">875°F is a temperature threshold for steel properties, beyond which certain phases may convert to graphite.&lt;SEP&gt;875°F is the temperature threshold above which the carbide phase of carbon–molybdenum steel may convert to graphite.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-8c9531d076f004c30f7355a51c50bbeb&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-37d20fead0ece91e4eb35b26f1cd873b</data>
      <data key="d4">ASME B16.5-2013.pdf</data>
      <data key="d5">1776329037</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="300">
      <data key="d0">300</data>
      <data key="d1">data</data>
      <data key="d2">300°C is a specific temperature point in the pressure-temperature ratings table, applicable for certain material groups and pressure classes. This temperature is also mentioned as a working pressure class in the ASME B16.5-2013 standard document. Additionally, 300 is noted as a pressure value in pounds per square inch gauge (psig), specifically representing the working pressure at 200°F for the 72Ni–15Cr–8Fe B564 Gr. N06600 material. While 300 is primarily associated with temperature and pressure, it is also referenced as a specific dimension value for ring-joint facings.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-44664e1f68bc892f4b7b0a535c4414b7&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-335c2335ba413830aae1a70244aa5a26&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-fb7c5babdbcd75bdf9752cd67bcadc21&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-94e58312a7e84066f13cc4e7ad9465d9&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-83ab283e30659c933554a033613d2618&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-1873d06e9a30c27b355fbcaa093fe77d&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-52ab56f901066385473a8c1877a7a0b4&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f9faa893029db6f5b871493c6380ddac&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-65a7f7e9599ea4d5c1cfc7d449c5a081&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-7934c8d2ddad5e1d33650120011594a2&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-2879e8ce1f305f975a2bf33f2d701842&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-30fa107e1afe5b6cba81caa3af7a1ab4</data>
      <data key="d4">ASME B16.5-2013.pdf</data>
      <data key="d5">1776329037</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Graphite">
      <data key="d0">Graphite</data>
      <data key="d1">artifact</data>
      <data key="d2">Graphite is a form of carbon that may form when certain materials are exposed to high temperatures.&lt;SEP&gt;Graphite is the product of carbide phase conversion in carbon–molybdenum steel when exposed to temperatures above 465°C.&lt;SEP&gt;Graphite is the product of carbide phase conversion in carbon–molybdenum steel at temperatures above 465°C.&lt;SEP&gt;Graphite is the product of the conversion of the carbide phase of carbon–molybdenum steel at temperatures above 875°F.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-8c9531d076f004c30f7355a51c50bbeb&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-a3453de580e274b0494108b0ff7189ee&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-fb7c5babdbcd75bdf9752cd67bcadc21&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-d88c25523fb6a395eb9e2724eb0719d5</data>
