    <node id="Chamfer">
      <data key="d0">Chamfer</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">Chamfer is a beveled edge or corner on a part, often used to reduce stress concentrations. This feature can be found on various components such as pipes, pipe fittings, and pipe flanges. Specifically, chamfer dimensions are detailed in relevant tables and standards. For instance, in ASME B16.5-2013, chamfer is defined as a beveled edge or corner on a pipe flange and also as a feature of the welding neck where the edge is beveled to facilitate welding. Additionally, chamfer can refer to an unthreaded length extending beyond the thread, as mentioned in one of the descriptions. Overall, chamfer serves to improve structural integrity by reducing stress concentrations and enhancing the ease of assembly and welding processes.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-c5f5e2c6bb85dac52bdfa7453796ec77&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b181980b1dcef22dc859d6b6b9c724e1&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-97992c13bd15395adccdb59249057965&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-5e85bee1a6414b667d34d9e3ddb49f16&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e27122e3377c1128b67882eafcae8b01&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-90c280892e81306b9d7b1a397e54f308&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e253e99ebed9a87e642e60132b8f53d9&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-9480b43d18d635d04248ae532bf3633c</data>
      <data key="d4">ASME B16.5-2013.pdf</data>
      <data key="d5">1776329045</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
